```json
{
  "application": "Singularity",
  "details": {
    "scheduler": "Slurm",
    "queue": "pinaki.sarder",
    "job name": "collagen_segmentation",
    "partition": "gpu",
    "gpus": "geforce:1",
    "nodes": 1,
    "tasks": 1,
    "cpus per task": 16,
    "memory": "80gb",
    "time": "25:00:00",
    "output": "collagen_seg_training_%j.out",
    "modules": "singularity",
    "environment variables": {
      "NEPTUNE_API_TOKEN": "eyJhcGlfYWRkcmVzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBwLm5lcHR1bmUuYWkiLCJhcGlfdXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hcHAubmVwdHVuZS5haSIsImFwaV9rZXkiOiJjNzllZGRmMC0yMzg2LTRhMzktOTk1MC1hNDc2MDlkNjVkYTMifQ=="
    },
    "container": "collagen_segmentation_latest.sif",
    "python script": "Collagen_Segmentation/CollagenSegMain.py",
    "script arguments": "train_inputs_single.json"
  }
}
```

The script runs a Singularity container named "collagen_segmentation_latest.sif". It utilizes Slurm for job scheduling and requires a GPU (specifically GeForce) and 16 CPUs per task. It also uses 80GB of memory and runs for a maximum of 25 hours. The script sets the NEPTUNE_API_TOKEN environment variable and runs a Python script named "CollagenSegMain.py" within the container.  It appears to be performing collagen segmentation training.
